00:04:23.400 --> 00:04:27.090
at the tomb of this
amazing human being whose

00:04:27.090 --> 00:04:31.290
poetry probably is unparalleled
in terms of how much he was

00:04:31.290 --> 00:04:36.860
able to create in his
lifetime, 27,500 poems.

00:04:36.860 --> 00:04:40.670
I'll never get there
in my lifetime.

00:04:40.670 --> 00:04:45.680
So it was here that I started
to receive information

00:04:45.680 --> 00:04:46.710
to write this book.

00:04:46.710 --> 00:04:48.890
In the story
"Damascena" is a story

00:04:48.890 --> 00:04:51.940
of an orphan girl who ends
up receiving a transmission

00:04:51.940 --> 00:04:54.320
to turn roses into
rose oil and she's

00:04:54.320 --> 00:04:56.800
mistaken as a saint for
performing miracles.

00:04:56.800 --> 00:04:59.080
She wants nothing to
do with this gift,

00:04:59.080 --> 00:05:01.620
and she's sent on a
mission to meet Rumi.

00:05:01.620 --> 00:05:06.420
And in this relationship
that she has with Rumi,

00:05:06.420 --> 00:05:08.390
he initiates her
into this dance,

00:05:08.390 --> 00:05:09.740
into the Whirling Dervish dance.

00:05:12.480 --> 00:05:14.610
And the Whirling
Dervishes, I don't

00:05:14.610 --> 00:05:16.800
know if anyone here
has actually seen them.

00:05:16.800 --> 00:05:19.470
They come to the Bay
Area quite frequently,

00:05:19.470 --> 00:05:21.770
I think once a year
at least, and this

00:05:21.770 --> 00:05:25.350
is a dance that is all
about turning inward.

00:05:25.350 --> 00:05:27.730
So it's a dance that goes
on for at least an hour

00:05:27.730 --> 00:05:32.270
with these dancers that are
literally turning in circles.

00:05:32.270 --> 00:05:36.960
So the idea of a dervish, you're
wondering what is a dervish.

00:05:36.960 --> 00:05:39.854
I'm sure we've all felt like
dervishes at some point,

00:05:39.854 --> 00:05:40.770
spinning and spinning.

00:05:40.770 --> 00:05:43.840
And in terms of
what the technology

00:05:43.840 --> 00:05:46.790
of this dance, the
dervish is actually one

00:05:46.790 --> 00:05:48.760
that is standing
on the threshold.

00:05:48.760 --> 00:05:50.830
That's the actual
translation of a dervish

00:05:50.830 --> 00:05:54.820
and that threshold is meant
to be the threshold of change

00:05:54.820 --> 00:05:56.400
and deep transformation.

00:05:56.400 --> 00:05:59.520
So this dance is an
opportunity for these people

00:05:59.520 --> 00:06:02.580
to turn inward toward something.

00:06:02.580 --> 00:06:07.550
And that something that they're
turning toward is the heart.

00:06:07.550 --> 00:06:10.342
And when we talk about
in everyday basis,

00:06:10.342 --> 00:06:11.550
we hear this in our language.

00:06:11.550 --> 00:06:14.560
And we've been aware of
ever since we've been a kid,

00:06:14.560 --> 00:06:16.360
you know listen to your heart.

00:06:16.360 --> 00:06:20.000
What is it that we're
listening to in our hearts

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:22.720
when people ask that question?

00:06:22.720 --> 00:06:25.640
Who's doing the
listening, right?

00:06:25.640 --> 00:06:28.830
So I'm going to unpack
that a little bit here.

00:06:28.830 --> 00:06:30.940
I'm also going to read
you one little excerpt so

00:06:30.940 --> 00:06:35.730
that you can actually see in
your mind what this dance is.

00:06:35.730 --> 00:06:37.710
This is the first time
this girl's actually

00:06:37.710 --> 00:06:39.950
experienced
witnessing the dance.

00:06:39.950 --> 00:06:41.766
And it's very odd to
her to see someone

00:06:41.766 --> 00:06:42.890
turning around in a circle.

00:06:42.890 --> 00:06:44.681
And the person that's
turning in the circle

00:06:44.681 --> 00:06:47.500
is Shams-- and Shams is
at this point in this book

00:06:47.500 --> 00:06:50.110
a very, very old man
and Shams of Tabriz

00:06:50.110 --> 00:06:53.080
was Rumi's most lauded
spiritual companion and probably

00:06:53.080 --> 00:06:59.350
the inspiration for the
majority of those 27,500 poems.

00:06:59.350 --> 00:07:01.670
And so this is
what it looks like.

00:07:01.670 --> 00:07:05.290
"She's watching him
from this little house.

00:07:05.290 --> 00:07:06.970
She moved to the
front window seeing

00:07:06.970 --> 00:07:09.620
the flicker of a small flame
burning in the fireplace

00:07:09.620 --> 00:07:12.430
in the hooded shadow of Shams's
twirling about the floor

00:07:12.430 --> 00:07:14.510
with his head tilted up.

00:07:14.510 --> 00:07:16.500
Her first instinct
was to giggle.

00:07:16.500 --> 00:07:19.030
She did not know the
old man could dance.

00:07:19.030 --> 00:07:20.710
He had complained
about his feet aching,

00:07:20.710 --> 00:07:24.210
but nothing about his
movement suggested pain.

00:07:24.210 --> 00:07:27.090
Shams wore an odd cone-shaped
hat look like an upside

00:07:27.090 --> 00:07:28.750
down flower pot.

00:07:28.750 --> 00:07:31.030
He moved in circles,
arms outstretched,

00:07:31.030 --> 00:07:34.880
mouth slightly open as he
drew in breath after breath,

00:07:34.880 --> 00:07:37.200
chanting words that
Damascena had never heard

00:07:37.200 --> 00:07:39.260
and could not understand.

00:07:39.260 --> 00:07:41.740
A confluence of accents
and vowels and rhythms

00:07:41.740 --> 00:07:44.350
that sounded much
like a waterfall.

00:07:44.350 --> 00:07:46.250
She liked the cleansing
calming effect

00:07:46.250 --> 00:07:48.700
even if she had no idea
what the man was saying

00:07:48.700 --> 00:07:51.130
between the thunder
and the rain."

00:07:51.130 --> 00:07:53.390
And this is an actual
poem from Rumi.

00:07:53.390 --> 00:07:57.630
" 'There is no salvation for
the soul but to fall in love.

00:07:57.630 --> 00:08:02.180
It has to creep and crawl
among the lovers first.' Shams

00:08:02.180 --> 00:08:04.990
repeated the verses over
and over, faster and faster,

00:08:04.990 --> 00:08:07.090
gaining speed in his twirling.

00:08:07.090 --> 00:08:09.420
His left foot was clenched
with a nail, wedged

00:08:09.420 --> 00:08:12.020
between his big toe and
the one after that, which

00:08:12.020 --> 00:08:15.490
seemed to keep him in place
while he spun in a circle.

00:08:15.490 --> 00:08:18.310
He reminded Damascena of
a little spinning top.

00:08:18.310 --> 00:08:20.675
And she was surprised he did
not topple over or collapse

00:08:20.675 --> 00:08:22.290
from dizziness.

00:08:22.290 --> 00:08:24.240
Watching him spin
soothed her in a way

00:08:24.240 --> 00:08:29.290
she had not felt
in a long time."

00:08:29.290 --> 00:08:32.260
So one of the things that you're
hearing in this little passage

00:08:32.260 --> 00:08:35.730
is this idea that it's
a deep intake of breath.

00:08:35.730 --> 00:08:38.470
So this dance is
coming from that place.

00:08:38.470 --> 00:08:41.280
It's a place-- it's a turning
inward toward the self

00:08:41.280 --> 00:08:43.520
and it's a turning
inward, and the irony

00:08:43.520 --> 00:08:45.630
is it's a turning and
a turning and a turning

00:08:45.630 --> 00:08:48.450
to actually
experience stillness.

00:08:48.450 --> 00:08:50.580
So when we talk
about this breath--

00:08:50.580 --> 00:08:52.710
and we're getting to the
technology of the heart

00:08:52.710 --> 00:08:55.040
here --everything
starts with the breath.

00:08:55.040 --> 00:08:57.770
It's about an intake
of breath, and when

00:08:57.770 --> 00:08:59.970
I talk about this
technology of the heart,

00:08:59.970 --> 00:09:02.080
it's actually all
about something

00:09:02.080 --> 00:09:03.640
that you all are aware of.

00:09:03.640 --> 00:09:08.170
And this is about coherence.

00:09:08.170 --> 00:09:09.640
It's about heart coherence.

00:09:09.640 --> 00:09:11.670
And it's not a
cognitive coherence.

00:09:11.670 --> 00:09:15.090
This is literally about
a coherent heart rhythm.

00:09:15.090 --> 00:09:17.520
And there's an institute
here in the Bay Area

00:09:17.520 --> 00:09:19.220
called the Institute
of HeartMath.

00:09:19.220 --> 00:09:23.510
And it was started by Doc
Childre and Rollin McCraty

00:09:23.510 --> 00:09:26.930
several years ago, and they've
actually done research now

00:09:26.930 --> 00:09:31.120
about how heart rhythms
affect our ability to think.

00:09:31.120 --> 00:09:35.770
And when you attain a particular
level of coherent heart

00:09:35.770 --> 00:09:37.890
rhythms-- and the
higher the amplitude,

00:09:37.890 --> 00:09:40.740
the better it is-- the
more focus you have,

00:09:40.740 --> 00:09:44.930
the less stress you have and
the more aligned you are.

00:09:44.930 --> 00:09:46.910
So when I saw this,
I thought that this

00:09:46.910 --> 00:09:48.200
is what this dance is.

00:09:48.200 --> 00:09:53.170
These Sufis were completely
dialed in to this technology

00:09:53.170 --> 00:09:55.150
without calling it technology.

00:09:55.150 --> 00:09:57.600
It was something rooted
in an ancient practice

00:09:57.600 --> 00:09:59.520
that the body was
aware of that it

00:09:59.520 --> 00:10:02.960
needed to do to actually
come into the stillness.

00:10:02.960 --> 00:10:06.100
So being a wordsmith, I can't
help but look at this word.

00:10:06.100 --> 00:10:08.330
Look at-- it's a
nine letter word.

00:10:08.330 --> 00:10:12.400
And the wild thing about
nine is that this dance

00:10:12.400 --> 00:10:15.770
is supposed to represent
the turning of the universe

00:10:15.770 --> 00:10:19.400
and the cosmos, as we are
turning with it every day.

00:10:19.400 --> 00:10:21.320
And so there's nine
letters in coherence.

00:10:21.320 --> 00:10:24.387
And there's nine dancers
that actually do the dance.

00:10:24.387 --> 00:10:26.220
When you actually see
the whirling dervishes

00:10:26.220 --> 00:10:29.280
dance in a group, it's
only nine dancers.

00:10:29.280 --> 00:10:32.590
So they're there to represent
that turning of the universe.

00:10:32.590 --> 00:10:35.470
And if you actually
break the word apart,

00:10:35.470 --> 00:10:38.990
there's a word "her"
and "hear" and "co."

00:10:38.990 --> 00:10:42.230
And to me, this is a
dialogue between the heart

00:10:42.230 --> 00:10:43.070
and the brain.

00:10:43.070 --> 00:10:47.180
It's a dialogue between, in
terms of the physiology of it,

00:10:47.180 --> 00:10:52.730
the intake of breath and the
listening for the inspiration

00:10:52.730 --> 00:10:54.910
and intuition.

00:10:54.910 --> 00:10:57.650
So clearly, if there's
an opportunity for you

00:10:57.650 --> 00:11:01.750
to increase your
heart coherence--

00:11:01.750 --> 00:11:04.390
and you literally can tap
into this in terms of getting

00:11:04.390 --> 00:11:06.060
hooked up to an EKG.

00:11:06.060 --> 00:11:08.941
And they can actually know
if you have coherent heart

00:11:08.941 --> 00:11:09.440
rhythms.

00:11:09.440 --> 00:11:11.590
I'll show you a
little bit in the top

00:11:11.590 --> 00:11:16.690
later what it looks like to have
incoherent heart rate or heart

00:11:16.690 --> 00:11:18.290
waves.

00:11:18.290 --> 00:11:23.430
So this whole idea in terms
of turning and grounding

00:11:23.430 --> 00:11:27.230
into yourself in order
to listen, when it gets

00:11:27.230 --> 00:11:28.960
back to listen to
your heart what

00:11:28.960 --> 00:11:31.000
is it that we're
actually listening to.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:34.190
So these Sufis
clearly were pretty

00:11:34.190 --> 00:11:38.310
sophisticated in understanding
what this particular dance

00:11:38.310 --> 00:11:41.600
could do and how transformative
it could be for people.

00:11:41.600 --> 00:11:44.470
And this is what Rollin
McCraty in his research--

00:11:44.470 --> 00:11:48.030
he's given me permission
today to use his research.

00:11:48.030 --> 00:11:50.910
But clearly, here
is the coherence.

00:11:50.910 --> 00:11:54.860
And the co, it's the
collaborative experience

00:11:54.860 --> 00:11:57.470
between this energetic
alignment and cooperation

00:11:57.470 --> 00:12:01.150
between the heart and
mind, body and spirit.

00:12:01.150 --> 00:12:04.730
It's pretty phenomenal in terms
of what these people could

00:12:04.730 --> 00:12:07.250
achieve just by doing a dance.

00:12:07.250 --> 00:12:11.000
But how do you do the dance
without doing the dance?

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:13.760
So William Blake, at the
time that this was actually

00:12:13.760 --> 00:12:16.220
starting to be recognized that
the heart was more than just

00:12:16.220 --> 00:12:20.220
an organ-- this was in
the late 19th century.

00:12:20.220 --> 00:12:23.167
And William Blake,
he was talking

00:12:23.167 --> 00:12:24.750
about this in this
quote here and he's

00:12:24.750 --> 00:12:26.290
saying "Man's
perceptions are not

00:12:26.290 --> 00:12:29.720
bounded by organs of
perception (the brain).

00:12:29.720 --> 00:12:33.290
He perceives far more than
sense (though ever so acute)

