00:38:55.995 --> 00:38:58.600
her back to the garden
where she collapsed and fell

00:38:58.600 --> 00:39:00.440
into a deep sleep.

00:39:00.440 --> 00:39:02.200
He watched over her
hearing the chatter

00:39:02.200 --> 00:39:04.720
of dervishes who had come
to pray over the girl hoping

00:39:04.720 --> 00:39:07.190
the dance had not killed her.

00:39:07.190 --> 00:39:09.520
Ivan wanted to assure
them that Damascena

00:39:09.520 --> 00:39:15.250
was alive, perhaps
more alive than ever."

00:39:15.250 --> 00:39:17.850
So with this understanding
that the brain is so much

00:39:17.850 --> 00:39:20.160
more than the heart, I have
to share with you something

00:39:20.160 --> 00:39:22.400
that literally came to
me in the mail yesterday.

00:39:22.400 --> 00:39:24.260
I don't know how
many people receive

00:39:24.260 --> 00:39:27.220
or write handwritten
letters anymore.

00:39:27.220 --> 00:39:29.280
This is from a
reader that I just

00:39:29.280 --> 00:39:31.420
met last month in Pennsylvania.

00:39:31.420 --> 00:39:34.410
And her daughter had
received a heart transplant,

00:39:34.410 --> 00:39:37.910
and I cannot tell you I got
this yesterday and I burst

00:39:37.910 --> 00:39:38.480
into tears.

00:39:38.480 --> 00:39:43.000
I couldn't believe it, and
I said I have to share this.

00:39:43.000 --> 00:39:45.730
They say the heart
is just a muscle.

00:39:45.730 --> 00:39:48.430
You and I know from
life-- with an underline

00:39:48.430 --> 00:39:53.670
on know and life --that it
is that and so much more.

00:39:53.670 --> 00:39:57.150
I see this with my daughter's
incredible gift of a heart.

00:39:57.150 --> 00:39:58.930
Saying goodbye to
her birth heart

00:39:58.930 --> 00:40:02.100
and welcoming her new heart
has been filled with gratitude

00:40:02.100 --> 00:40:06.600
and just about every other
emotion known to man.

00:40:06.600 --> 00:40:10.750
So how will you step into
this place in your heart

00:40:10.750 --> 00:40:15.210
to experience an enlivening in
yourself here in the workplace,

00:40:15.210 --> 00:40:15.710
beyond.

00:40:18.900 --> 00:40:21.960
So on this first
day of fall, I'm

00:40:21.960 --> 00:40:24.910
going to ask you how you're
going to lead with your heart

00:40:24.910 --> 00:40:27.350
and I want you to
interact with me.

00:40:27.350 --> 00:40:30.890
So send me a message and
let me know how it goes.

00:40:30.890 --> 00:40:33.790
I'm so curious, it's
all very subtle.

00:40:33.790 --> 00:40:36.430
Thank you so much for having me.

00:40:36.430 --> 00:40:38.150
RACHEL O'MEARA: Thanks, Holly.

00:40:38.150 --> 00:40:41.020
We'll open it up to
questions or comments

00:40:41.020 --> 00:40:43.960
if anyone has any
in the audience.

00:40:43.960 --> 00:40:45.850
AUDIENCE: So Holly,
I'm curious what

00:40:45.850 --> 00:40:49.250
got you to Turkey,
to Konya, Turkey.

00:40:49.250 --> 00:40:51.140
HOLLY PAYNE: I was
there to do research

00:40:51.140 --> 00:40:54.010
for "The Virgin's Knot," which
I was researching the rug

00:40:54.010 --> 00:40:54.510
industry.

00:40:54.510 --> 00:40:58.000
And I happened to live with the
rug merchant and his family.

00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:02.580
And his cousin said,
do you know Rumi?

00:41:02.580 --> 00:41:05.690
I said no, should
I and he laughed.

00:41:05.690 --> 00:41:07.420
Now I know why he laughed.

00:41:07.420 --> 00:41:09.600
You silly American
girl, he said.

00:41:09.600 --> 00:41:13.030
And every taxi cab driver
could quote from Rumi.

00:41:13.030 --> 00:41:15.140
And I thought I need to know.

00:41:15.140 --> 00:41:19.030
When he took me to the tomb,
it was literally electrifying.

00:41:19.030 --> 00:41:20.950
And I had no idea who he was.

00:41:20.950 --> 00:41:24.020
And when I came back, that
started the whole process.

00:41:24.020 --> 00:41:27.030
And I started to read Coleman
Barks, just a really simple

00:41:27.030 --> 00:41:28.210
translation.

00:41:28.210 --> 00:41:30.670
It's an extraordinary book.

00:41:30.670 --> 00:41:33.660
But in terms of what
the West has access to,

00:41:33.660 --> 00:41:35.180
it's a little decimal.

00:41:35.180 --> 00:41:38.180
Think about 27,000 poems.

00:41:38.180 --> 00:41:40.320
We only have a tiny little bit.

00:41:40.320 --> 00:41:41.360
And it's not in Persian.

00:41:41.360 --> 00:41:43.260
I wish I could read
and speak Persian

00:41:43.260 --> 00:41:46.400
because just to hear the
musicality of the poetry

00:41:46.400 --> 00:41:48.166
would be great.

00:41:48.166 --> 00:41:50.290
AUDIENCE: How do you envision
connecting technology

00:41:50.290 --> 00:41:51.567
with the heart?

00:41:51.567 --> 00:41:54.150
HOLLY PAYNE: You mean how could
technology actually connect us

00:41:54.150 --> 00:41:55.210
to our hearts?

00:41:55.210 --> 00:41:56.957
AUDIENCE: Yes, that's
a better question.

00:41:56.957 --> 00:41:58.540
HOLLY PAYNE: I think
there's many ways

00:41:58.540 --> 00:42:01.410
that we can start
engaging with the heart.

00:42:01.410 --> 00:42:04.400
I actually know of a woman
here in San Francisco that

00:42:04.400 --> 00:42:08.660
has actually created a
probe that you can wear,

00:42:08.660 --> 00:42:10.430
and you can go home
and download it.

00:42:10.430 --> 00:42:15.160
I'm a cyclist, so I know there's
an app for something called

00:42:15.160 --> 00:42:17.700
Strava and you
actually can-- you

00:42:17.700 --> 00:42:19.530
know how much
mileage you've done,

00:42:19.530 --> 00:42:21.436
it's geo-coded so they
know where you are.

00:42:21.436 --> 00:42:23.060
That's good and bad,
sometimes you just

00:42:23.060 --> 00:42:26.500
want to get out on the road and
have no one know where you are.

00:42:26.500 --> 00:42:30.660
But in terms of understanding
where your heart coherence,

00:42:30.660 --> 00:42:32.360
you can actually get feedback.

00:42:32.360 --> 00:42:35.210
And there's a lot
of games out there--

00:42:35.210 --> 00:42:38.120
the HearthMath Institute
has a lot of different ways

00:42:38.120 --> 00:42:39.020
to engage people.

00:42:39.020 --> 00:42:44.520
I actually worked with
someone who knows Dr. McCraty.

00:42:44.520 --> 00:42:47.370
And he had me sit down
with a video game.

00:42:47.370 --> 00:42:52.960
And it literally was-- if you
had coherent heart rhythms,

00:42:52.960 --> 00:42:55.610
you could actually go
on around the world

00:42:55.610 --> 00:42:57.970
in this balloon,
this hot air balloon.

00:42:57.970 --> 00:43:01.950
And so be very
aware of my breath.

00:43:01.950 --> 00:43:04.010
And then you get timed
for how long you're

00:43:04.010 --> 00:43:05.940
able to stay in
coherent heart rhythm.

00:43:05.940 --> 00:43:09.290
So you basically travel
all over the world.

00:43:09.290 --> 00:43:10.970
I think I got down
into the Grand Canyon

00:43:10.970 --> 00:43:13.136
and my balloon was cruising
around the Grand Canyon.

00:43:13.136 --> 00:43:18.590
But there's ways that they're
engaging this through videos.

00:43:18.590 --> 00:43:21.400
I was just at a launch
of a new program

00:43:21.400 --> 00:43:23.040
here in San
Francisco called Arc.

00:43:23.040 --> 00:43:26.930
And it's the fusion of
technology and health,

00:43:26.930 --> 00:43:28.080
and medicine.

00:43:28.080 --> 00:43:32.337
And there was a
researcher from UCSF,

00:43:32.337 --> 00:43:33.920
and he literally has
created something

00:43:33.920 --> 00:43:35.490
where you can step
inside the brain.

00:43:35.490 --> 00:43:36.990
And they've talked
about how they're

00:43:36.990 --> 00:43:40.260
using video games to help kids
who have Attention Deficit

00:43:40.260 --> 00:43:42.630
Disorder, depression,
and so forth.

00:43:42.630 --> 00:43:44.930
And the video game
itself is actually

00:43:44.930 --> 00:43:49.180
helping to change the
physiology of the body.

00:43:49.180 --> 00:43:51.420
And it's actually
creating healing.

00:43:51.420 --> 00:43:54.190
And we also know the detrimental
effects of that kind of media

00:43:54.190 --> 00:43:55.510
as well.

00:43:55.510 --> 00:43:57.760
So it's a great question to ask.

00:43:57.760 --> 00:44:00.124
And so being here
and speaking, I

00:44:00.124 --> 00:44:02.040
wanted to ask the question
so everyone else is

00:44:02.040 --> 00:44:04.010
starting to ask
the question, too.

00:44:04.010 --> 00:44:05.850
Because there is an
app, there should

00:44:05.850 --> 00:44:07.530
be an app for this thing.

00:44:07.530 --> 00:44:09.110
I mean if there's
so much information

00:44:09.110 --> 00:44:11.960
here, let's tap into it.

00:44:11.960 --> 00:44:17.010
Just tap in to the power of
that imagination and intuition

00:44:17.010 --> 00:44:19.767
and bring it all together.

00:44:19.767 --> 00:44:21.350
AUDIENCE: I've had
straight up debates

00:44:21.350 --> 00:44:24.830
with close friends of mine on
whether to listen to your head

00:44:24.830 --> 00:44:26.120
or to your heart.

00:44:26.120 --> 00:44:28.160
And I have my own
answer but I just

00:44:28.160 --> 00:44:30.860
wanted to leave that
open ended and hear

00:44:30.860 --> 00:44:33.990
what you had to say about that
or what you would tell someone

00:44:33.990 --> 00:44:36.400
that's struggling on
which one to listen to

00:44:36.400 --> 00:44:38.860
or which one it is in general.

00:44:38.860 --> 00:44:41.000
HOLLY PAYNE: Well
it's a great question

00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:42.710
I think we all struggle with it.

00:44:42.710 --> 00:44:45.620
I mean I don't think there's
one person, unless you're

00:44:45.620 --> 00:44:49.127
at that level of consciousness,
which I certainly am not.

00:44:49.127 --> 00:44:51.460
I don't know if I'll ever
achieve that in this lifetime,

00:44:51.460 --> 00:44:54.245
but I am certainly
humbled by the endeavour.

00:44:57.720 --> 00:45:01.120
I think that the brain
plays an extraordinary role.

00:45:01.120 --> 00:45:04.130
I mean without the brain, there
is a two way communication

00:45:04.130 --> 00:45:05.840
going on here.

00:45:05.840 --> 00:45:09.970
But I think we, in this
culture especially,

00:45:09.970 --> 00:45:14.390
we are so overdeveloped
in this part of our brain,

00:45:14.390 --> 00:45:15.490
in that frontal lobe.

00:45:15.490 --> 00:45:18.810
It is so overdeveloped, where
you literally you literally

00:45:18.810 --> 00:45:23.480
feel like you're-- it's
like you're burning up.

00:45:23.480 --> 00:45:25.080
As a writer, I can
feel that because I

00:45:25.080 --> 00:45:27.320
feel I always go forward.

00:45:27.320 --> 00:45:31.170
And this is my writing line.

00:45:31.170 --> 00:45:35.500
And when I go back, when
I actually shift my--

00:45:35.500 --> 00:45:38.180
where I am inside myself,
I know that sounds crazy,

00:45:38.180 --> 00:45:40.850
but when I come from a place
that's not from my head,

00:45:40.850 --> 00:45:42.850
I literally am dropping down.

00:45:42.850 --> 00:45:44.779
So this idea of
leaning forward, I

00:45:44.779 --> 00:45:46.320
don't want to get
into a huge debate,

00:45:46.320 --> 00:45:48.990
but to me, it's about
let's lean back.

00:45:48.990 --> 00:45:53.750
Like lean back, lean
back, get quiet.

00:45:53.750 --> 00:45:56.089
If that person has the
courage to listen--

00:45:56.089 --> 00:45:58.130
a lot of times the reason
we don't want to listen

00:45:58.130 --> 00:46:00.940
to the heart is because it's
going to give us information

00:46:00.940 --> 00:46:03.450
that's pretty much going to
require something that all

00:46:03.450 --> 00:46:05.470
of you here-- you
might be programmers.

00:46:05.470 --> 00:46:08.930
In the world of tech, you
understand the word pivot.

00:46:08.930 --> 00:46:12.350
Pretty much it's going to
be an invitation to pivot.

00:46:12.350 --> 00:46:14.050
For another word,
it just means it's

00:46:14.050 --> 00:46:17.530
an invitation, an opportunity
to change something.

00:46:17.530 --> 00:46:20.980
Anytime you have a
kernel of the truth,

00:46:20.980 --> 00:46:27.240
clearly something is not
true and it's not aligned.

00:46:27.240 --> 00:46:29.040
But that truth is
usually going to require

00:46:29.040 --> 00:46:33.140
us to do something that's not
going to be so comfortable.

00:46:33.140 --> 00:46:35.520
That's why I-- my
own personal belief

00:46:35.520 --> 00:46:39.234
--is why we don't engage
the heart as much.

00:46:39.234 --> 00:46:41.150
Because it's going to
require a little change,

00:46:41.150 --> 00:46:43.870
it's going to require
a little sobering up

00:46:43.870 --> 00:46:47.220
to the fact like where am I
out of alignment with myself.

00:46:47.220 --> 00:46:49.350
If you think your
way through it,

00:46:49.350 --> 00:46:52.405
pretty much nine times out
of 10, actually 10 times out

00:46:52.405 --> 00:46:55.600
of 10, you're not
always going to have

00:46:55.600 --> 00:46:58.040
the best information coming.

00:46:58.040 --> 00:47:01.850
You can use your brain
to sort it out afterward.

00:47:01.850 --> 00:47:06.950
But it's more of why do I
know that this relationship is

00:47:06.950 --> 00:47:10.790
actually causing my disease.

00:47:10.790 --> 00:47:12.017
Why do I know that?

00:47:12.017 --> 00:47:12.850
There's no evidence.

00:47:12.850 --> 00:47:14.720
I can't go to a
doctor and say I'm

00:47:14.720 --> 00:47:17.490
feeling this way because
of this relationship.

00:47:17.490 --> 00:47:19.260
Your body knows.

00:47:19.260 --> 00:47:21.200
We know this kind of stuff.

00:47:21.200 --> 00:47:24.000
The brain is a wonderful-- it's
like in the writing process,

00:47:24.000 --> 00:47:25.790
I have to write
from the bottom up.

00:47:25.790 --> 00:47:28.020
I always encourage people
when I work with them.

00:47:28.020 --> 00:47:31.490
When a story comes, really
check out where it comes from.

00:47:31.490 --> 00:47:33.940
And where does it
sit in your body?

00:47:33.940 --> 00:47:36.740
And right from this place
up, not from this place down.

00:47:36.740 --> 00:47:40.060
I love to engage my brain
when I have to do editing

00:47:40.060 --> 00:47:42.240
and really looking
at story design.

00:47:42.240 --> 00:47:45.450
But to know that the
foundation's there,

00:47:45.450 --> 00:47:49.270
the heart to me gives rise to
the foundation for everything.

00:47:49.270 --> 00:47:52.135
I mean Steve Jobs
said it best, right?

00:47:52.135 --> 00:47:56.270
The heart will always
lead you, it'll know.

00:47:56.270 --> 00:47:59.540
And this is the guy that we
look at as one of the smartest,

00:47:59.540 --> 00:48:04.320
most literally brilliant,
brilliant people that

00:48:04.320 --> 00:48:05.970
lived during our time.

00:48:05.970 --> 00:48:08.560
And what's that source
of the brilliance?

00:48:08.560 --> 00:48:10.570
To me it's like,
wow, I would love

00:48:10.570 --> 00:48:13.120
to have seen Steve Jobs'
magnetic field in terms

00:48:13.120 --> 00:48:15.730
of just his love for technology.

00:48:15.730 --> 00:48:21.740
His love to develop something
that never been done before.

00:48:21.740 --> 00:48:23.950
So it will always be a debate.

00:48:23.950 --> 00:48:25.700
It will always be a
debate, because that's

00:48:25.700 --> 00:48:27.480
where the fear is.

00:48:27.480 --> 00:48:29.700
The question was
asked to Damascena,

00:48:29.700 --> 00:48:31.790
you're spinning so fast,
and spinning so fast,

00:48:31.790 --> 00:48:33.640
our minds are "pfft."

00:48:33.640 --> 00:48:36.240
The minds are the
whirling dervishes.

00:48:36.240 --> 00:48:38.080
But the heart helps
to slow you down,

00:48:38.080 --> 00:48:42.040
or you can slow down the
heart to actually allow

00:48:42.040 --> 00:48:46.750
the communication to serve you.

00:48:46.750 --> 00:48:50.200
If you're willing to be
aligned with the truth,

00:48:50.200 --> 00:48:51.900
that's the bigger question.

00:48:51.900 --> 00:48:56.080
You can say, what you are
afraid of, to your friend.

00:48:56.080 --> 00:48:59.160
AUDIENCE: I had a
question about HeartMath.

00:48:59.160 --> 00:49:01.095
I don't know them
well, but are they--

00:49:01.095 --> 00:49:03.300
you may not know it
either --but are they

00:49:03.300 --> 00:49:06.325
working with companies, or is
it more just research based.

00:49:06.325 --> 00:49:08.680
It sounds so interesting
that they're just--

00:49:08.680 --> 00:49:08.730
HOLLY PAYNE: You
know, that's a great

00:49:08.730 --> 00:49:09.010
AUDIENCE: dedicated
to find that.

00:49:09.010 --> 00:49:10.190
HOLLY PAYNE: --question.

00:49:10.190 --> 00:49:12.540
And I can put you in
touch with Dr. McCraty.

00:49:15.090 --> 00:49:17.100
I know that they do teach this.

00:49:17.100 --> 00:49:20.050
So they teach something called
a freeze frame technique.

00:49:20.050 --> 00:49:23.550
And the appreciation
one, it was kind

00:49:23.550 --> 00:49:27.039
of a really diluted version.

00:49:27.039 --> 00:49:29.080
But I wanted to just show
you how simple it could

00:49:29.080 --> 00:49:33.120
be just based on, you don't
even have to brand it.

00:49:33.120 --> 00:49:36.090
It's just like, let's
actually feel an appreciation,

00:49:36.090 --> 00:49:39.250
and just experience
physiologically what that does.

00:49:39.250 --> 00:49:41.410
And what that did
actually, in the room,

00:49:41.410 --> 00:49:45.310
is it actually magnified
that heart field.

00:49:45.310 --> 00:49:49.290
All of us, our heart field
was totally untrained.

00:49:49.290 --> 00:49:52.740
So if you can do
that on your team,

00:49:52.740 --> 00:49:56.010
all those little rocks line up.

00:49:56.010 --> 00:49:58.740
It's not about loving
everything all the time,

00:49:58.740 --> 00:50:01.990
it's about creating
harmonious outcomes.

00:50:01.990 --> 00:50:03.990
Harmonious outcomes
might require the brain

00:50:03.990 --> 00:50:06.210
to think through some
things and strategize,

00:50:06.210 --> 00:50:08.090
but if you have that
discourse from a place

00:50:08.090 --> 00:50:11.330
of the heart versus
a competitive place,

00:50:11.330 --> 00:50:14.390
you're literally going to have--
the chances are --everyone

00:50:14.390 --> 00:50:16.870
engaged in that
communication, in that moment,

00:50:16.870 --> 00:50:20.650
is having higher heart
rhythm coherence.

00:50:20.650 --> 00:50:23.130
Versus someone
bringing you down,

00:50:23.130 --> 00:50:26.680
and we want to run
from those folks.

00:50:26.680 --> 00:50:28.740
AUDIENCE: Do have a
favorite Rumi poem?

00:50:28.740 --> 00:50:30.910
HOLLY PAYNE: Do I have
a favorite Rumi poem?

00:50:30.910 --> 00:50:34.230
Yes, and please don't put
me on the spot to quote it,

00:50:34.230 --> 00:50:35.892
but I can paraphrase it.

00:50:35.892 --> 00:50:37.350
And it's the "Guest
House," I think

00:50:37.350 --> 00:50:38.720
many, many people know it.

00:50:38.720 --> 00:50:43.190
And for me, just in terms of
my own recent personal life,

00:50:43.190 --> 00:50:46.370
I've had many things showing
up and requiring change.

00:50:46.370 --> 00:50:48.670
And requiring really
a deep listening

00:50:48.670 --> 00:50:51.760
and getting honest with
me with what aligned

00:50:51.760 --> 00:50:53.410
and what's not aligned.

00:50:53.410 --> 00:50:56.080
And so the "Guest
House" in a nutshell--

00:50:56.080 --> 00:50:58.610
sorry Rumi, forgive
me if I butcher this,

00:50:58.610 --> 00:51:02.100
but I'm going to paraphrase
in the best way I can.

00:51:02.100 --> 00:51:05.006
Is basically-- there's going to
be a lot of people and things

00:51:05.006 --> 00:51:06.630
that are going to
show up in your life.

00:51:06.630 --> 00:51:10.790
And he says welcome them all
for they may be clearing you out

00:51:10.790 --> 00:51:13.460
